               <interp inst="t18560514-495" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18560514"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18560514-495" type="date" value="18560514"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18560514-495-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-495-18560514 t18560514-495-offence-1 t18560514-495-verdict-1"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18560514-495-charge-2" targOrder="Y" targets="def2-495-18560514 t18560514-495-offence-1 t18560514-495-verdict-1"></join>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185605140235"></xptr>
               <p>495. <persName id="def1-495-18560514" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-495-18560514" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-495-18560514" type="age" value="36"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-495-18560514" type="surname" value="SWILSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-495-18560514" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM SWILSON</hi>
                  </persName> and <persName id="def2-495-18560514" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-495-18560514" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-495-18560514" type="age" value="38"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-495-18560514" type="surname" value="MARSHALL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-495-18560514" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JAMES MARSHALL</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18560514-495-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18560514-495-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18560514-495-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp>, stealing 49<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. in money, of <persName id="t18560514-name-230" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-230" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-230" type="surname" value="GREGORY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-230" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18560514-495-offence-1 t18560514-name-230"></join>Robert Gregory</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. RYLAND</hi>. <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-231" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-231" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-231" type="surname" value="GREGORY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-231" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT GREGORY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an emigrant, about to sail in the <hi rend="italic">Sea King</hi> for Australia; she is now lying in the London Docks. On Thursday, 1st May, I saw Marshall on board the <hi rend="italic">Sea King</hi>—he introduced himself to me as a gentleman going out by the same ship, and said that he had some machinery on board—after talking with him on board for some time about the Colonies and other matters, he got me to walk off with him as far as the Spread Eagle, in Graoechurch-street—from thence he proposed going for a stroll to see the sights of London, and he took me to a public house near West-minster Bridge, and treated me with a glass of ale and a biscuit—while we were there, Marshall came in, he fined me and Swilson—he said that he had just come from America in consequence of an uncle haying left him a great deal of money—he pulled out his money, and showed several notes, end several sovereigns, and seemed greatly rejoiced—he said that he would treat us with a glass each to drink his health, which he did—this was about 3 o'clock in the afternoon—Swilson then proposed that we should go to Cremorne Gardens—we all three left the public house together, and walked about different streets—I am not much acquainted with London—we after<lb></lb>wards took a boat—we then went to another public house near Cremorne Gardens—I know it was near Cremorne Gardens, I had beer there—while we were in that public house Swilson gave me a small bag, and also Marshall, and he also said he would give us an American dollar each, to keep for his sake—there was nothing in the bag that he gave me—I had at that time in my possession a bag containing about fifty sove-reigns, among it there were two old guineas—there had been 50<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., sovereigns and half sovereigns, I had changed one half sovereign—my bag was within another bag, about the same size and colour as tins one (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>)—I took my bag out of my pocket, and put it on the table before Swilson—Swilson took it up, and also this bag, and said he would put it in for me with the American dollar—he appeared to do so, bag and all, tied it up, and returned it to me, and I put it into my pocket, thinking that I had got my money right—shortly after we all three left the house together—when we had got a little way Swilson said, "I hare forgot my pocket handkerchief, which can run the fastest?"—the other hesitated, and I turned back and ran to see if there was any pocket handkerchief left behind, but there was no pocket handkerchief—I then returned to the spot where I had left the prisoners, and they were both gone—I did not look at my money then—it roused my suspicions, and as soon as I pulled it out, I found my money was gone—I cannot tell at what time that was, it was at some time in that evening—I believe it was as I was going to pay for my breakfast—it must have been next morning, therefore—I Slept at some public house at Ken<lb></lb>sington that night—I went to see a cousin, and then to the public house where I slept—next morning, when I was going to pay for my breakfast, I took out my bag and opened it, and none of my sovereigns were there, nor the two guineas, nor the American dollar, but a quantity of farthings, I think more than fifty; part of them are here, the other part I had to pay for my breakfast with, as I had no more money in my pocket—I then gave information to the police—I had never seen the prisoners before—I am perfectly satisfied they are the men.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What time was it when Swilson came into the public house near Westminster Bridge? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I should think about 3 o'clock—it was</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185605140236"></xptr>
               <p>nearly 5 o'clock when they went away—we had been together more than two hours.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METCALFE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Where was it you slept? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I do not know the name of the public house—I slept alone, and locked myself in—after the prisoners went away, at 5 o'clock, I walked straight on to my cousin's, at Kensington—I went to bed early, before 10 o'clock; it might be about 9 o'clock—I sat with jny cousin, and we had a glass of ale at the public house where I lodged, and a journeyman with him—my cousin then went home, and I went to bed—I first drank a glass of ale with the prisoners, then a glass of brandy and water at the Victoria tavern, and one glass of brandy and water at the place where Swilson came in—I should say we had about three in the course of the day—I believe we went to three public houses—I will not swear we had no more; I will swear we had not a great deal—I never was drunk in my life.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How came you to pull out your money, and allow them to shift it into a different bag? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> From their respectable appearance and manner, I thought they were gentlemen—I had not the slightest suspicion of them—immediately I found they were gone, I put my hand into my pocket, and felt that my bag was all right; I did not look inside until I went to pay for my breakfast—I gave a description of the prisoners, and was for some time looking after them, and Mr. Smith and an officer, 63 <hi rend="italic">F</hi>, I believe, came to me, and said they had taken a person on suspicion from my description—I went with them to the station, and saw Swilson in the cell—I looked at him, and hesitated at first; I said his features were like, but his dress and appearance was so much altered that I doubted for the moment; but when I came to hear him speak, and saw him with his other coat on, I had not the slightest hesitation in saying he was the man—we afterwards went with him in a <hi rend="italic">cab</hi> somewhere—he pulled his hat off in the <hi rend="italic">cab</hi>, and said to me, "Look at me again, and be very careful, for it is a very serious charge; you are quite mistaken in the man," or something of that sort—I did not make any answer—I did not, when the charge was being booked at the police station, say that Swilson had whiskers and eyes like the man, but that I was not positive about him—Swilson told the Magistrate that I had said so, and the Magistrate asked me if I had any doubt about him, and I said, "No, not the least"—Smith did not tell me that he was the man—he said that he had given a person into custody whom he called <hi rend="italic">Flash Harry</hi>, and he pre<lb></lb>sumed he was the man from the description I had given, and wanted me to go and see him—I had not seen either of the prisoners before to my knowledge.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. RYLAND</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What change was there in Swilson's dress and appear<lb></lb>ance? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He was so shabby, and dirty, and untirly—when I saw him before, his appearance and manner were like a gentleman.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-232" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-232" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-232" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-232" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES SMITH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am agent to the Maritime Insurance Company, in Fenchurch-street. I know the two prisoners—I think I have known Swilson four or five years, and Marshall from one to two years—I have frequently seen them together—I do not believe that Swilson has been to America for the last year or two; he has not been at all to my knowledge—I have seen him frequently, perhaps two or three times a month, during the last year—it is possible he may have gone out in a very fast steamer, and just come back again, but I do not think he could have done it; it is barely possible; I am only speaking from recollection.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Crss-examined. Q.</hi> You are agent to the Maritime Insurance Society? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I am a regularly appointed agent by the Company—I am the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185605140237"></xptr>
               <p>London agent; we have very fine offices at No. 113, Fencburch-street; my office is there, and the office of the Company—the Company rents it—it is a regularly chartered Company—they gave me a certain salary, fifty guineas a year, and ten per cent, commission on all policies—the salary is simply for expenses—I have not been to Liverpool or Manchester since June or July last—I resided at Liverpool many years—I have been a good deal at Man<lb></lb>chester—I have not been a good deal before the Magistrates there—I have never been in the dock—I have been a witness there, I suppose two, three, or four times; three times within the last four or five years—some of these characters that you defend say I am a sort of amateur policeman—I never receive any money for it, not for my expenses—I have never pocketed my expenses; I have always given them to the officer in the case—I do it on public grounds—I have never made any mistake—it is not true that a woman was wrongly convicted on my evidence at Manchester, and after<lb></lb>wards pardoned—I do not recollect any woman being convicted there of picking pockets on my evidence, and being afterwards pardoned, because it was found out that I was wrong—I never heard of it—I will not swear it is not true—I have not given evidence a dozen times at Manchester; perhaps three or four times; it might be five—I will not swear it was not half a dozen; I will swear it was not a dozen—I have given evidence a great many times at Liverpool, perhaps twenty or thirty—I do not know how many times in London; two or three times, perhaps—you may not see these things; perhaps you have not the observation—I lived at Liverpool seven<lb></lb>teen years, and have received the thanks of the Magistrates, and of the Judges—I left Liverpool to suit myself; I prefer London in every way as a place for business—I have been before Mr. Maude, the Magistrate, at Man<lb></lb>chester; he knows me very well; it is an infamous fabrication to say that Mr. Maude ever told me that he wished not to see me there again, and that the police were much better without my services than with them—he never said anything of the kind; he has thanked me once or twice from the bench—any expenses I might get I hare always given to the officer employed in the case—I have never received any expenses in London; I have not been a witness here—I do not recollect the names of any officers in Liverpool or Manchester to whom I have handed over my expenses.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How came you to have anything to do with helping the police? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Merely on public grounds; wherever I can be of any service I do it—I became connected with this case through the captain of the <hi rend="italic">Sea King</hi>, who is a particular friend of mine, and, hearing the description of the men, I thought I knew them—Swilson used to live at Liverpool—I did not know Where lie lived at the time this matter occurred—I knew one house that he did reside in, and I sent the officer there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-233" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-233" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-233" type="surname" value="HANSCOMB"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-233" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS HANSCOMB</persName>
                  </hi>. (<hi rend="italic">policeman, F</hi> 63). I took Swilson into custody on Friday morning, about 10 o'clock, near Exeter-hall, in the Strand—I told him I took him on suspicion of stealing fifty sovereigns from a gentleman near Cremorne—he said he was innocent of the charge—Mr. Smith gave me information; in consequence of which, I found the prosecutor, and took him to the station to see Swilson, and he identified him as one of the men who had robbed him—he was alone in the dock when he saw him—we gene<lb></lb>rally show several prisoners together, but he was the only one we had there then—I took Marshall into custody about 7 o'clock, that same evening, in the Strand—the prosecutor was with me, and pointed him out—I told him the charge—he uaid, "Oh"—I took hold of the cuff of his coat, and he said, "Well, lift my arm up, so that you won't show me up"—I searched him,</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185605140238"></xptr>
               <p>and found on him thirteen sovereigns, half a crown, and a counterfeit coin like a half sovereign—we asked the prisoners their addresses at the station, and they refused to give them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Have you ever been in a case with Smith before? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Never—I did not know that I was going to get his fees—I should not take them without reporting it to the Commissioners—if I did I should be dis<lb></lb>charged—there is a rule against it—Mr. Smith has not said anything to me about giving me bis fees—Swilson said he was innocent—he said Smith had never seen him before in his life, and that he was setting the prosecutor on to him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">SWILSON</hi>—<hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18560514-495-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
